artist: Dick Miller & The Rhythmasters / Al, Larry & The Untouchables
comment1: Al Huntzinger (drums) and Larry Fountain (guitar) split from Dale Thomas & The Bandera Boys to start their own band – Al, Larry & The Untouchables.
Mr. “Mission Bell” returns to Danceland. Donnie is back on the charts with his latest Top 40 hit “Doll House”.

artist: Leonard Reyman & His Orchestra featuring Jeanne Hunt
The Drifters / Eddie Randall & The Downbeats
Bobby Lord / Bobby Hankins & The Blue Boys
comment1: Bobby returns for his third and final Danceland appearance. This might have been his last appearance because he was ticked off when someone stole his guitar after the gig.
Conway’s latest is a rockin’ redo of “C’est Si Bon” which is currently on the national charts.

artist: Bill Black Combo / Gary Stites / Gene Simmons
comment1: Bill Black first gained fame as Elvis Presley’s original bass player. He would tour and record with Elvis until 1958 when they parted ways. In 1959 Black formed his own combo and signed with Hi Records out of Memphis. Their first hit “Smokie – Part 2” went gold. The combo also earned gold records for “White Silver Sands” and “Josephine”. Their instrumental version of Elvis’ “Don’t Be Cruel” was also a big hit and a popular number in their live show. The confirmed combo members at Danceland that night were Bill Black (bass), Hank Hankins (guitar), Bobby Emmons (piano), Jerry (Jerome) Arnold (drums).
comment2: Gary returns for his fourth and final time.
comment3: No, this isn’t the Gene Simmons of the make-up clad ‘70s shock-rock band KISS. This is “Jumpin’ Gene” Simmons the rockabilly singer/songwriter from Tupelo, Mississippi. Gene’s current record is “Goin’ Back To Memphis”. Gene would return to headline at Danceland in 1964 when he was touring to support his hit “Haunted House”.

artist: Dick Miller & The Rhythmasters / Al, Larry & The Untouchables
Pug's Western Playboys / Eddie Randall & The Downbeats
Bobby Vee / The Ventures / The Checkers
comment1: Like a rubber ball Bobby comes bouncing back to Danceland. He followed up his big hit “Devil Or Angel” with the equally big “Rubber Ball”. His current release is a two-sided charter “Stayin’ In” / “More Than I Can Say”.
comment2: Fans didn’t walk – they ran down to Danceland to see the Ventures. Don Wilson (rhythm guitar), Bob Bogle (lead guitar), Nokie Edwards (bass) and Howie Johnson (drums) formed in the Seattle/Tacoma, Washington area. Their first hit proved to be a rock and roll classic. “Walk - Don’t Run”. They also charted high with a rocked-up version of “Perfidia”. Their current instrumental is “Ram-Bunk-Shush”.
comment3: The Checkers were from Yakima, Washington. Their guitarist (future jazz star Larry Coryell) wasn’t able to join the guys on this tour due to school obligations. The confirmed members of the Checkers that night were Mike Metko (sax) and Doug Robertson (drums). It is believed the other band members were Joe Johanson (guitar), Mike Mandel (piano), Dick Ruthardt (bass).

artist: Leonard Reyman & His Orchestra featuring Jeanne Hunt
The Fendermen / Bobby Hankins & The Blue Boys
caption1: The Fendermen were inducted into the Iowa Rock ‘n’ Roll Association’s Hall of Fame in 1997.

artist: Leonard Reyman & His Orchestra featuring Jeanne Hunt
Danny & The Juniors / Dicky Doo & The Don'ts / Johnny Maestro / Gerry Granahan
comment1: Danny & the Juniors return. Their first two hits, “At The Hop” and “Rock And Roll Is Here To Stay”, have become classics. Their current charter is “Pony Express”.
comment2: Dicky Doo & the Don’ts were formed by Gerry Granahan and featured Ray Gangi (guitar), Harvey Davis (bass), Al Ways (sax) and Dave Alldred (drums). Their first release “Click-Clack” clicked with the teens and would reach 28 on the charts. Gerry Granahan would also appear on this bill as a solo artist.
comment3: Johnny first appeared at Danceland back in September of 1960 when he was the lead singer for the Crests (“16 Candles”). Johnny has since gone solo and his first effort was “Model Girl” which made the Top 20. His later releases didn’t fare as well. In 1968 Johnny would form the Brooklyn Bridge and score a gold single with “Worst That Could Happen”.
comment4: Singer / songwriter / record producer Gerry Granahan was born in Pittston, Pennsylvania. In 1958 Gerry signed with Sunbeam Records and released “No Chemise Please” a song inspired by the ‘50s “sack dress” clothing fad. The song became a nationwide hit, peaking at #23 on the Billboard Hot 100. Gerry also formed the group Dicky Doo & the Don’ts. He has since signed with Gone Records and his current release was “Look For Me”. Granahan would later form Caprice Records and produce hits for the Fireflies (“You Were Mine”), Dicky Doo & the Don’ts (“Nee Nee Na Na Na Na Nu Nu”) and the Angels (“’Til”).

artist: Louis DeKlotz & His Orchestra / Howdy Roberts

comment1: Country music superstar Buck Owens’ career was just getting started when he played his only Danceland date. Alvis Edgar “Buck” Owens was born in Sherman, Texas but made his mark in the music business when he moved to Bakersfield, California. It was there that Buck developed the “Bakersfield Sound” that would propel him to stardom. Buck had enjoyed several country hits before he played at Danceland – “Second Fiddle”, “Under Your Spell Again”, “Above And Beyond” and “Excuse Me (I Think I’ve Got A Heartache)”. His current release was the two-sided hit “Foolin’ Around” b/w “High As The Mountains”. Buck would go on to record an incredible twenty-one #1 country hits including “Act Naturally” and “I’ve Got A Tiger By The Tail”. He would also co-host the Hee Haw TV show with Roy Clark.
caption1: Buck Owens was inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame in 1996.

artist: Larry Verne / Dick Miller & The Rhythmasters
comment1: Larry Verne Erickson was born in Minneapolis, Minnesota. His family moved to the Los Angeles area in his youth where he found work as a carpenter. He was working in a recording studio the same time producers / songwriters Fred Darian, Al DeLory and Joe Van Winkle were recording a novelty number they had written. The session was going well except they didn’t feel they had the right voice for the song. Larry was nearby and they asked him to put down his hammer and give it a try. He did, and Larry’s life changed forever. “Mr. Custer” turned out to be one of the best-selling novelty records of the ‘60s. It went all the way to # 1 and earned Larry a gold record. Larry followed “Mr. Custer” up with the similar-sounding “Mister Livingston”. His current release was “Abdul’s Party”.
Singer/showman Donnie Brooks makes his third and final appearance at Danceland. He’s back on the charts with his third Top 100 hit in a row, “Memphis”.

artist: Leonard Reyman & His Orchestra featuring Jeanne Hunt
Del Shannon / The String-A-Longs / Ersel Hickey
comment1: Del Shannon was born Charles Weedon Westover in Grand Rapids, Michigan. Del and keyboard player Max Crook performed together as members of Charlie Johnson and the Little Big Show band in Battle Creek, Michigan. Del got signed to Big Top Records and recorded a song he wrote with Max wrote called “Runaway”.  It was a runaway hit going straight to #1, staying there for four weeks and going gold. The song featured a unique sounding keyboard called a Musitron played by Max.
comment2: The String-A-Longs were from the exciting sounding town of Plainsview, Texas. The band lineup that played at Danceland that night was Richard Stephens (lead guitar), Keith McCormack (guitar), Jimmy Torres (guitar), Aubrey de Cordova (bass) and Don Allen (drums). The guys got their start in the recording field when Keith’s mother saved up enough money for the guys to pay for a session at the famed Norman Petty Studios. Norman Petty Studios was picked because of its stellar reputation - and the fact that it was a mere 90 miles away! They were then known as the Leen Teens and that first session produced the song “So Shy”. Petty was able to place the track with Imperial Records, but it failed. They moved over to the Warwick label and changed their name to the String-A-Longs. In January their rocking instrumental “Wheels” would hit #3. Their latest chart entry is “Brass Buttons”.
comment3: Ersel Hickey was born in Brighton, New York. Ersel’s claim to musical fame is two-fold. His first feat-of-note was “Bluebirds Over The Mountain”. Ersel wrote the song and got Epic Records interested. Even though it only charted at #75 it has become a rockabilly classic. Second was his iconic publicity photo. Shot in Buffalo by Gene LaVerne the image of Ersel with his slicked-back hair, cocked knees and clutching the guitar like he was clutching a rifle has become an iconic rocker image from the era. At the time of his Danceland appearance Ersel was signed to Kapp Records and his latest release was “Teardrops At Dawn”.

artist: Pee Wee Hunt & His 12th Street Ragtime Band
comment1: Trombonist / vocalist / band leader Pee Wee Hunt was born Walter Gerhardt Hunt in Ohio. He was the featured trombonist in the Casa Loma Orchestra before forming his own band. His biggest hit and signature song was “Twelfth Street Rag”.

artist: The Aristocrats with Mary on vocals
Tony Orlando / B. Bumble & The Stingers / Cathy Jean / The Roommates / Ral Donner
comment1: Tony Orlando was born Michael Anthony Orlando Cassavitis in New York City. He was discovered by music producer Don Kirshner. He has just released his first Top 40 hit “Halfway To Paradise” written by Carole King and Gerry Goffin. Most remember Tony as part of the popular ‘70s group Tony Orlando & Dawn.
comment2: B. Bumble & the Stingers were a group of talented L.A. session musicians led by Ernie Freeman. They recorded a frantic rock reworking of Rimsky-Korsakov’s “Flight Of The Bumble Bee” and titled it “Bumble Boogie”. Rendezvous Records released the song and it became a big hit – charting at #21. The studio musicians were too booked up to go on the road to promote the disc, so a touring group was put together. Known members of B. Bumble & the Stingers that night were Fred Richards (piano), Butch Parker (bass / sax) and Ron Brady (drums). They have just released their follow-up “Boogie Woogie”.
comment3: Cathy Jean Giordano was from Brooklyn, New York. The Valmor label signed Cathy Jean and recorded “Please Love Me Forever”. The label owners, Gene and Jody Malis, managed the Roommates singing group and had them supply the background vocals for the record. DJ “Murray the K” stared playing the disc and it rose to #12.
comment4: The Roommates were from Queens, New York and consisted of Steve Susskind (lead), Bob Minsky (bass), Jack Sailson (tenor) and Felix Alvarez (tenor). After suppling vocals for Cathy Jean’s hit, they put out a record of their own. They dusted off the old Benny Goodman chestnut “Glory Of Love” and updated it for the growing teenage audience. It made the national Top 50.
comment5: Ralph Stuart Emanuel Donner was born in Norwood Park, Chicago. He’s on the charts with his first hit “Girl Of My Best Friend”. It probably didn’t hurt that Ral sounded a bit like Elvis.
caption1: The Roommates were from Queens, New York and consisted of Steve Susskind (lead), Bob Minsky (bass), Jack Sailson (tenor) and Felix Alvarez (tenor). After suppling vocals for Cathy Jean’s hit, they put out a record of their own. They dusted off the old Benny Goodman chestnut “Glory Of Love” and updated it for the growing teenage audience. comment1: This is Dion’s first Danceland appearance since parting ways with the Belmonts. His solo career is off to a great start. His first single, “Lonely Teenager”, was a big hit. His current 45 is “Somebody Nobody Wants”.
caption1: Dion on stage with the Fendermen

artist: Leonard Reyman & His Orchestra featuring Jeanne Hunt

comment1: Country singer/songwriter/guitarist Bobby Bare was born in Ironton, Ohio. He recorded a demo of a song he’d written called “The All American Boy”. Bobby left the demo at Fraternity Records but ended up getting drafted shortly after. While Bobby was in the service Fraternity erroneously released the song as by Bill Parsons. Later pressings corrected the mistake.

artist: Leonard Reyman & His Orchestra featuring Jeanne Hunt

comment1: The Shadows were the band that backed Bobby Vee during his early recording and touring years. In fact, Bobby’s first hit, ”Suzie Baby” was billed as Bobby Vee & the Shadows. The Shadows featured Bobby’s older brother Bill Velline (guitar), Bob Korum (drums) and Dick Dunkirk (bass). Bobby was not an official member of the group but remained in the shadows. The intent was to create a separate identity for the Shadows away from Bobby. They formed their own record label (Vee) and released “Leave Me Alone” / “What’ll I Say” in 1960. Bobby was involved with the producing and songwriting for the band but took a back seat after that.  When Bobby was tied up or on the west coast recording the Shadows would take some dates without him.

artist: Ray Ruff / Chuck Tharp / The Checkmates
comment1: A couple of guys from Norman Petty studios make their way to Danceland.
comment2: Ray Ruff was born Marvin Ray Ruffin in Amarillo. Texas. In his youth he befriended Buddy Holly and through Buddy he met Buddy’s producer Norman Petty. Ray joined the staff of Petty’s Clovis, New Mexico recording studio. Petty groomed Ray as Buddy’s replacement and assembled a backing band dubbed the Checkmates.
comment3: Chuck Tharp was a founding member and the original vocalist of the Fireballs. He was also part of the group of musicians that worked out of Norman Petty’s studio in Clovis, New Mexico.

comment1: The Flairs return to Danceland only this time they’re going by their new name, the Velaires. They cut a super version of Chuck Berry’s “Roll Over Beethoven” for the Palms label. The record started to garner some attention in the Midwest. It also came to the attention of record producer Buck Ram. He had a group with the same name but spelled differently - Flaires (of “Foot Stompin’” fame). Ram thought the band’s name would cause confusion with the record buying public and threatened legal action. To avoid any problems the Flairs changed their name to the Velaires (supposedly after the Vel Air Ballroom in Des Moines) and signed to Jamie Records out of Philadelphia. Jamie was able to get the fellas on American Bandstand and distributed “Roll Over Beethoven” on a national level. The record would peak at #51
caption1: The Velaires were inducted into the Iowa Rock ‘n’ Roll Association’s Hall of Fame in 1997.

comment1: Bobby’s back. His latest, “Sailor Man”, is a Midwest hit. It’s #35 on the Chicago’s WLS Silver Dollar Survey. Bobby would later have major hits with “Detroit City” and “500 Miles From Home”.

artist: Leonard Reyman & His Orchestra featuring Jeanne Hunt
Ral Donner / Ray Stevens / Tony Orlando / Janie Grant / Bobby Vinton / The Prep Tones
comment1: Ral was just here in June. He has followed up “Girl Of My Best Friend” with an even bigger hit “You Don’t Know What You’ve Got (Until You Lose It)” which would hit #4.
comment2: Ray Stevens was born Harold Ray Ragsdale in Clarkdale, Georgia. At age seventeen he moved to Atlanta where he met radio personality/publisher/label owner Bill Lowery. Bill signed Ray to his label, NRC, and released several songs Ray had written including the novelty ditty “Sergeant Preston Of The Yukon”. The moderate success of “Sergeant Preston” got him a deal with Mercury Records. His first Top 40 hit “Jeremiah Peabody’s Poly Unsaturated Quick Dissolving Fast Acting Pleasant Tasting Green And Purple Pills” has the distinction of being the longest song title in the rock and roll era.
comment3: Tony O. returns to Danceland for the second time this year. He has followed up his first hit “Halfway To Paradise” with “Bless You”.
comment4: Janie Grant was born Rose Marie Cosili in Patterson, New Jersey. She was signed to Caprice Records and had a Top 30 hit with “Triangle” earlier in the year. She just released “Romeo”.
comment5: Bobby Vinton’s singing career was just getting started in 1961.He was newly signed to Epic Records and his first release was “Well I Ask Ya”.  Well you don’t need to ask what happened to this song – it didn’t dent the charts. This would be the last time Bobby would be featured this far down on a bill. Next summer he would release “Roses Are Red (My Love)” and earn headliner status.

artist: Johnny Burnette / Bobby Hankins & The Blue Boys
comment1: Johnny was here about a year ago on a six-person bill. He’s now elevated himself to headlining status. Since his big hit “Dreamin’” he’s had an even bigger one with “You’re Sixteen”.

artist: The Sparks / The Bop Cats / The Ravens
Dick & Dee Dee / Jan & Dean / Jerry Fuller / The Checkers
comment1: This was Dick & Dee Dee’s first tour of the Midwest. Their single “The Mountain’s High” was a west coast hit and they were out on a national tour hoping to turn it into a national hit. The strategy worked – “The Mountain’s High” would peak at #2. Their five-song set that night was “The Mountain’s High” the flip side “I Want Someone” along with “Love Is Strange”, “Swing Low, Sweet Chariot” and “What’d I Say”.
comment2: Jan Berry and Dean Torrence had some success before they helped usher in surf music craze. They had a Top 10 hit with “Baby Talk” back in 1959. They also had Top 100 chart success with “We Go Together”, “Clementine” and “Gee”. This summer they had “Heart And Soul”. Their current effort is “Wanted, One Girl”.
comment3: In 1959 Jerry Fuller moved to Los Angeles from Fort Worth, Texas and secured a recording contract with Challenge Records. He cut a rockabilly version of Patti Page’s “Tennessee Waltz” that hit #63. At the time of this appearance his release was “Guilty Of Loving You” that just snuck into the Top 100. Although Jerry never got that big breakthrough hit as a singer, his songwriting and producing talents would lead to an incredibly successful career in the music business behind the scene. Jerry wrote “Travelin’ Man”, “It’s Up To You”, “Young World” and “A Wonder Like You” for Rick Nelson. He discovered the Knickerbockers and produced their 1965 hit “Lies”. He also discovered Gary Puckett & the Union Gap. Fuller wrote and produced their hits “Young Girl”, “Lady Willpower”, and “Over You”. He worked with O.C. Smith and produced “Son Of Hickory Holler’s Tramp” and “Little Green Apples”. In 1973 he wrote and produced the #1 hit “Show And Tell” by Al Wilson. Not too bad for a guy you probably never heard of.
comment4: Backing everyone up was the Checkers - Joe Johansen (guitar), Mike Mandel (piano), Dick Ruthardt (bass) and Doug Robertson (drums). Joe Michaelson has replaced Mike Metko on sax.

artist: Dion / Roscoe & The Little Green Men
comment1: Dion returns for the second time this year (he was here in June). His latest release, “Runaround Sue”, was currently moving up the charts where it would peak at #1 and go gold. It would be one of Dion’s biggest hits.

artist: Jimmy Dean / Al, Larry & The Untouchables
comment1: ”Big Bad John” wasn’t Jimmy’s first hit. Way back in 1953 he hit the Top 5 with “Bumming Around” but he experienced a lengthy eight-year dry spell after that. That drought came to an end in 1961. That’s when Jimmy recorded a story-song he had written about a heroic miner. “Big Bad John” was a big, bad hit. It was an across-the-board smash - #1 Pop, #1 Country, #1 Adult Contemporary! It earned a gold record and won a Grammy Award.
caption1: Jimmy Dean was inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame in 2010.

artist: Johnny Cash / Johnny Western / Eddie Randall & The Downbeats
comment1: The “Man In Black” returns for his lucky seventh time. This time he’s got his buddy Johnny Western with him. Both Johnny’s have recent hits with current western TV show theme songs. Cash with “The Rebel – Johnny Yuma” and Western with “The Ballad Of Paladin” from “Have Gun - Will Travel”.
comment2: Singer/songwriter/actor Johnny Western was born in country music hot bed of Two Harbors, Minnesota. He grew up idolizing Gene Autry and dreaming of someday becoming a singing cowboy. After experiencing some local success, he migrated to California in the mid-fifties. In 1956 Johnny’s dream came true when he was hired to replace Johnny Bond in his hero Gene Autry’s band. When Autry retired in 1957 Johnny was signed by Autry’s agent, Mitchell Hamiburg. That association led to acting roles in the several western movies and TV shows. After acting on an episode of “Have Gun - Will Travel” (starring Richard Boone) Johnny was inspired to write “The Ballad Of Paladin” which would become the show’s closing theme song. In 1958 Johnny Cash hired label-mate Western to be a featured performer and master of ceremonies for his road show. They would also record together in the studio.
